/contacts
/contacts/[id]
/integrations
/billing
/settings
```

## Mapping note
- route `/results` maps to workflow table `research_results`
- database naming and route naming are allowed to differ

---

# 4. Feature Folder Responsibility

Each folder under `features/` owns domain UI implementation.

Example:
- forms
- domain-specific components
- domain-specific views
- domain hooks
- schemas
- domain services

## Example
`features/results/`
- results-inline-table.tsx
- result-detail-view.tsx
- result-actions.tsx
- result.schemas.ts

---

# 5. feature-system Responsibility

This folder owns runtime feature/module gating.

It decides:
- which modules are visible
- which features are enabled
- which actions are disabled and why
- which provider-backed capabilities are available

The rest of the app must consume this layer, not duplicate entitlement logic.

---

# 6. Results Naming Rule

The official UI/domain name is `results`, not `research-results`.

Use:
- route = `results`
- feature folder = `features/results`
- entity folder = `entities/results`
- service folder = `services/results`

Database table remains:
- `research_results`

---

# 7. AI-Friendly Implementation Rule

To make future implementation easy:
- one feature folder per module
- one feature-system layer for entitlement logic
- one service layer per domain
- one shared view system
- one global organization context

This prevents duplicated logic and keeps the app extensible.

---

# 8. Final Rule

If a developer is unsure where code belongs:

- If it decides **whether a capability is available**, it belongs in `feature-system/`
- If it renders **how a module looks or behaves**, it belongs in `features/`
- If it defines **reusable layouts for inline/detail/form**, it belongs in `views/`
- If it talks to Supabase/backend, it belongs in `services/`
